name: Sylvia A. Earle
text: The most dangerous pandemic is complacency. It is not too late to make peace with Nature. Why wait?

name: Sylvia A. Earle
text: Extraction of ocean wildlife on an industrial scale not only is morally and ethically barbaric; it undermines the processes that make our existence possible. It is baffling why so many have for so long regarded nature as free for the taking. And here we are.

name: Sylvia A. Earle
text: Using the ocean as the ultimate dumpsite is having catastrophic consequences, but what is being removed may be causing even greater harm.

name: Sylvia A. Earle
text: The focus now is on terrestrial species and ecosystems while the distress to ocean stability may have even greater impact through changes to planetary chemistry and temperature, largely governed by the ocean.

name: Sylvia A. Earle
text: Restoring stability to disrupted systems and treating the natural world as if our lives depend on it may be our best hope for an enduring future. Not a new message!

name: Sylvia A. Earle
text:
What is now happening with COVID-19 has been predicted and as long as we continue to abuse nature more pandemics are inevitable. 

https://t.co/T8lyiTJGgw

text: A7 How often do you eat animals that are older than you? Why is it different for wildlife from the ocean? #fishforthought

text: A5 Some people rely on artisanal fishing for survival. A bigger problem is poorly regulated industrial-scale fishing!! #fishforthought

name: Sylvia A. Earle
text: A4 I encourage a diet of all or mostly plants, and if you want, w/ small amounts of meat from plant-eating animals. #fishforthought

name: Sylvia A. Earle
text: .@DannaMoorePfahl It could be, but let's be careful. Best to do it on land. Escaped farmed species into the ocean contaminates gene pools.

name: Sylvia A. Earle
text: .@chevewhiro @MissionBlue The good news is you can stop and still get those great nutrients. Look into plant-based alternatives.

name: Sylvia A. Earle
text: A3 Eating big fish like tuna/sharks is like eating lions & other predators critical to the food web. Would you eat a lion? #fishforthought

name: Sylvia A. Earle
text: .@CRWS2014 @MissionBlue Way to go you guys!!

name: Sylvia A. Earle
text: A2 I avoid it. I prefer fish swimming in the ocean, not in lemon slices & butter! It's a choice I encourage others to make. #fishforthought

name: Sylvia A. Earle
text: .@KimLawther Why not both?
